'We need a $1 trillion tax cut'
Published 1:00 am, Wednesday, April 14, 2009
Caption
WASHINGTON -- President Barack Obama is making a pitch to a key Democratic lawmaker to pass tax cuts, even as he tries to avoid the issue in public statements.
"There's only one way to jump-start the economy, and that is for the federal government to step in," Obama said in a recent interview with The Hill. "That's the only way to get people back to work and get this economy to grow and create jobs."
Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev., has been the one member of Congress who has pushed hardest, if somewhat unsuccessfully, to get tax relief passed.
In an interview with The Washington Post on Tuesday, the Senate majority leader said he hoped to have the $1 trillion tax cut proposal wrapped up by the middle of next week, when Congress is scheduled to leave town.
Obama said the country's tax system should be simplified and streamlined so that taxpayers are not "confused" and "conflicted" over what deductions to take. He also suggested a $5 trillion package of tax cuts, ranging from an extension of jobless benefits to tax relief on energy production.
Obama also said he would seek to reduce the corporate tax rate, from the current 35% to 28% and then to 25%. Obama has previously called for a tax cut for all taxpayers, not just those who have paid the most in recent years.
Obama said that the tax proposal would help the country out of its "deep recession." He said he would not rule out any ideas, including a payroll tax holiday, that could help boost the economy.
The president also said Obama's plan was to pay for the tax cuts through spending cuts.

“I don’t want to play semantics here, but I do believe that the term that Donald Trump likes to use is ‘fake news,’ because he does not like certain news stories.
“But when you’re talking about fake news, I mean fake news is actually fake news.

9/11 plotters' 'biggest fear: They'd never make it to martyrdom'
CNN
(CNN) - As 9/11 plotters prepare to mark the 10th anniversary of the Sept. 11, 2001 attacks in the United States, the nation's top intelligence official warns "there is evidence that there is a link between 9/11 and Iraq's weapons of mass destruction."
"There is evidence that there is a link between 9/11 and Iraq's weapons of mass destruction program," says James Clapper, the director of national intelligence, during a news briefing Thursday.
But it was a different message from President's Barack Obama. In his weekly radio and video address on Saturday, Obama said the Iraq war "was based on the best intelligence we had -- and I'll never second-guess the decision that we made."
CNN has been working on this story for the last week in conjunction with The New York Times. In its reporting, we are told that Iraq was never directly linked to 9/11.
But the question for U.S. intelligence is whether Iraq had a "co-perpetrator" role in the plot that led to 9/11. And in a report last month to Congress, Clapper said that "there is no credible intelligence to support allegations that Iraq had a role." The report was based on "a review of intelligence on Iraq's alleged WMD programs."
But a new report by a U.S. intelligence committee has said that "the intelligence community believes that Saddam Hussein's regime had an active effort to develop weapons of mass destruction (WMD) before, during and after its invasion of Kuwait on July 8, 1990."
